      <h1>How to Calculate Percentage: 3 Easy Formulas</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Percentages come up everywhere — in shopping discounts, tax calculations, tip amounts, grade calculations, investment returns, and countless other daily scenarios. Despite being one of the most common math operations, many people find percentages confusing. The good news is that virtually every percentage problem falls into one of three categories, and each category has a simple formula. This guide teaches you all three formulas with clear, worked examples for each, provides a reference table for common percentage calculations, shares mental math shortcuts that let you calculate percentages in your head, and explains the often-confused difference between percentages and percentage points.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>The Three Percentage Formulas You Need</h2>
    <p>Every percentage problem you encounter can be solved with one of these three formulas:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Formula 1:</strong> Find X percent of Y &rarr; Result = Y &times; (X / 100)</li>
      <li><strong>Formula 2:</strong> What percent is X of Y? &rarr; Percentage = (X / Y) &times; 100</li>
      <li><strong>Formula 3:</strong> Percent increase or decrease &rarr; Change = ((New - Old) / Old) &times; 100</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Let us work through each formula in detail with multiple real-world examples.</p>

    <h2>Formula 1: Find X Percent of Y</h2>
    <p>This is the most common percentage calculation. You use it whenever you need to find a specific percentage of a given number. The formula is:</p>
    <p><strong>Result = Y &times; (X / 100)</strong></p>
    <p>In plain English: multiply the total by the percentage, then divide by 100. Alternatively, you can convert the percentage to a decimal first (divide by 100), then multiply.</p>

    <h3>Example 1: Sales Tax</h3>
    <p>You buy a laptop for 899 and the sales tax is 8.25 percent. How much is the tax?</p>
    <p>Tax = 899 &times; (8.25 / 100) = 899 &times; 0.0825 = 74.17</p>
    <p>The tax is 74.17, making the total 973.17.</p>

    <h3>Example 2: Restaurant Tip</h3>
    <p>Your dinner bill is 67.50 and you want to leave an 18 percent tip. How much is the tip?</p>
    <p>Tip = 67.50 &times; (18 / 100) = 67.50 &times; 0.18 = 12.15</p>
    <p>The tip is 12.15, making the total 79.65.</p>

    <h3>Example 3: Discount Shopping</h3>
    <p>A jacket originally costs 120 and is on sale for 35 percent off. How much do you save, and what is the sale price?</p>
    <p>Discount = 120 &times; (35 / 100) = 120 &times; 0.35 = 42.00</p>
    <p>You save 42.00. The sale price is 120 - 42 = 78.00.</p>
    <p>For instant calculations on shopping discounts, try our <a href="/discount-calculator/">discount calculator</a>.</p>

    <h2>Formula 2: What Percent Is X of Y?</h2>
    <p>Use this formula when you know two numbers and want to express one as a percentage of the other. The formula is:</p>
    <p><strong>Percentage = (X / Y) &times; 100</strong></p>
    <p>In plain English: divide the part by the whole, then multiply by 100.</p>

    <h3>Example 1: Test Score</h3>
    <p>You answered 42 questions correctly out of 50. What is your score as a percentage?</p>
    <p>Percentage = (42 / 50) &times; 100 = 0.84 &times; 100 = 84 percent</p>
    <p>Your test score is 84 percent.</p>

    <h3>Example 2: Budget Tracking</h3>
    <p>Your monthly income is 4,500 and you spent 1,350 on rent. What percentage of your income goes to rent?</p>
    <p>Percentage = (1,350 / 4,500) &times; 100 = 0.30 &times; 100 = 30 percent</p>
    <p>Rent takes up 30 percent of your income.</p>

    <h3>Example 3: Savings Goal</h3>
    <p>You want to save 15,000 for a down payment and you have saved 6,750 so far. What percentage of your goal have you reached?</p>
    <p>Percentage = (6,750 / 15,000) &times; 100 = 0.45 &times; 100 = 45 percent</p>
    <p>You are 45 percent of the way to your savings goal. Use our <a href="/percentage-calculator/">percentage calculator</a> to check your own calculations instantly.</p>

    <h2>Formula 3: Percent Increase or Decrease</h2>
    <p>This formula calculates how much something has changed relative to its original value. It is essential for understanding price changes, investment returns, salary raises, and any situation involving growth or decline. The formula is:</p>
    <p><strong>Percent Change = ((New Value - Old Value) / Old Value) &times; 100</strong></p>
    <p>A positive result indicates an increase; a negative result indicates a decrease.</p>

    <h3>Example 1: Salary Raise</h3>
    <p>Your salary increased from 55,000 to 59,400. What was the percentage raise?</p>
    <p>Percent Change = ((59,400 - 55,000) / 55,000) &times; 100 = (4,400 / 55,000) &times; 100 = 8.0 percent</p>
    <p>You received an 8.0 percent raise.</p>

    <h3>Example 2: Stock Market Loss</h3>
    <p>A stock dropped from 82 per share to 61.50. What is the percentage decrease?</p>
    <p>Percent Change = ((61.50 - 82) / 82) &times; 100 = (-20.50 / 82) &times; 100 = -25.0 percent</p>
    <p>The stock decreased by 25.0 percent.</p>

    <h3>Example 3: Home Value Appreciation</h3>
    <p>You bought a house for 320,000 and it is now worth 412,800. What is the percent increase?</p>
    <p>Percent Change = ((412,800 - 320,000) / 320,000) &times; 100 = (92,800 / 320,000) &times; 100 = 29.0 percent</p>
    <p>Your home has appreciated by 29.0 percent. Use our <a href="/percentage-change-calculator/">percentage change calculator</a> for quick percent increase or decrease calculations.</p>

