    <h2>Percentage vs. Percentage Points</h2>
    <p>This is one of the most commonly confused concepts in math, finance, and journalism. The difference between "percent" and "percentage points" is significant and getting it wrong can lead to major misunderstandings.</p>

    <h3>The Distinction Explained</h3>
    <p><strong>Percentage points</strong> measure the arithmetic difference between two percentages. If a mortgage interest rate goes from 6 percent to 8 percent, it has increased by <strong>2 percentage points</strong>.</p>
    <p><strong>Percent change</strong> measures the relative change. That same rate increase from 6 percent to 8 percent represents a <strong>33.3 percent increase</strong> (because 2 is 33.3 percent of 6).</p>

    <h3>Why It Matters: Real-World Examples</h3>
