            <th>Percentage Point Change</th>
            <th>Percent Change</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Tax rate: 5% &rarr; 7%</td>
            <td>+2 percentage points</td>
            <td>+40%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Unemployment: 4% &rarr; 6%</td>
            <td>+2 percentage points</td>
            <td>+50%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Savings rate: 0.5% &rarr; 4.5%</td>
            <td>+4 percentage points</td>
            <td>+800%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Market share: 30% &rarr; 25%</td>
            <td>-5 percentage points</td>
            <td>-16.7%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Approval rating: 52% &rarr; 48%</td>
            <td>-4 percentage points</td>
            <td>-7.7%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Notice how the savings rate example is particularly dramatic: a 4 percentage point increase from 0.5 percent to 4.5 percent represents an 800 percent increase. News outlets and politicians sometimes exploit this ambiguity, using whichever framing makes a change sound larger or smaller depending on their narrative. Always pay attention to whether "percent" or "percentage points" is being used.</p>

    <h2>Percentage Formulas for Everyday Situations</h2>
    <p>Here are the specific percentage calculations you are most likely to need in daily life, with the exact formulas laid out:</p>

    <h3>Calculating a Discount</h3>
    <p>Discounted Price = Original Price &times; (1 - Discount Percent / 100)</p>
    <p>Example: 25 percent off a 160 item. Discounted Price = 160 &times; (1 - 25 / 100) = 160 &times; 0.75 = 120.</p>

    <h3>Adding Sales Tax</h3>
    <p>Total Price = Pre-Tax Price &times; (1 + Tax Rate / 100)</p>
    <p>Example: 8 percent tax on 45.99. Total = 45.99 &times; (1 + 8/100) = 45.99 &times; 1.08 = 49.67.</p>

    <h3>Finding the Original Price Before a Discount</h3>
    <p>Original Price = Sale Price / (1 - Discount Percent / 100)</p>
    <p>Example: An item is on sale for 63 after a 30 percent discount. Original = 63 / (1 - 30/100) = 63 / 0.70 = 90.</p>

    <h3>Calculating Grade Percentages</h3>
    <p>Grade Percent = (Points Earned / Total Points Possible) &times; 100</p>
    <p>Example: You earned 847 points out of 1,000. Grade = (847 / 1,000) &times; 100 = 84.7 percent.</p>

    <h3>Determining Required Test Score</h3>
    <p>Required Score = (Target Grade &times; Total Weight - Current Weighted Score) / Remaining Weight</p>
    <p>Example: You want a 90 percent overall grade. You have scored 87 percent on assignments worth 60 percent of your grade. You need: (90 &times; 100 - 87 &times; 60) / 40 = (9,000 - 5,220) / 40 = 94.5 percent on the final exam.</p>

