    <h2>Compound Percentages: Why They Do Not Simply Add Up</h2>
    <p>A common mistake is assuming that consecutive percentage changes can be added together. They cannot, and understanding why is important for financial literacy.</p>
    <p><strong>Example: A stock gains 20 percent and then loses 20 percent. Are you back to even?</strong></p>
    <p>No. If you start with 1,000 and gain 20 percent, you have 1,200. If you then lose 20 percent of 1,200, you lose 240, leaving you with 960. You are actually down 4 percent from your starting point, not back to even. This happens because the 20 percent loss applies to the larger number (1,200), not the original (1,000).</p>
    <p><strong>Example: A product goes on sale for 30 percent off, and you have an additional 20 percent off coupon. Is that 50 percent off?</strong></p>
    <p>No. If the original price is 100, the 30 percent discount brings it to 70. The additional 20 percent off applies to 70, giving you a further 14 off, for a final price of 56. That is a total discount of 44 percent, not 50 percent. Stacked discounts always result in less savings than their simple sum.</p>

    <h2>Percentage Calculations in Finance</h2>
    <p>Percentages are the language of finance. Here are the key financial percentage concepts you should understand:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>APR (Annual Percentage Rate):</strong> The yearly interest rate charged on borrowing, including fees. A 24 percent APR on a 5,000 credit card balance means approximately 1,200 per year in interest (though compounding makes the actual amount slightly higher).</li>
      <li><strong>APY (Annual Percentage Yield):</strong> The yearly return on savings or investments, accounting for compound interest. A 4.5 percent APY on 10,000 in savings yields 450 per year.</li>
      <li><strong>Inflation rate:</strong> The percentage by which average prices increase over a year. A 3 percent inflation rate means something that costs 100 today will cost approximately 103 next year.</li>
      <li><strong>Return on investment (ROI):</strong> ROI = (Profit / Cost) &times; 100. If you invest 5,000 and sell for 6,500, your ROI is (1,500 / 5,000) &times; 100 = 30 percent.</li>
      <li><strong>Down payment percentage:</strong> The portion of a purchase price paid upfront. A 20 percent down payment on a 350,000 home is 70,000.</li>
    </ul>

